any changes at all, did he?

458
00:32:28,655 --> 00:32:32,700
We made very few changes in England.

459
00:32:34,911 --> 00:32:38,914
We worked on that precision, you know.

460
00:32:39,041 --> 00:32:42,877
I remember it was May. We were going
to start shooting in September.

461
00:32:43,003 --> 00:32:47,506
I think it was May,
and he said, "You know, Al..."

462
00:32:47,591 --> 00:32:49,884
I said, "I think we're ready.
We've got the script."

463
00:32:49,968 --> 00:32:54,138
And he said, "Yes, but I want
this cross to the window,

464
00:32:54,306 --> 00:32:58,142
"and I don't think we have it yet."
I said, "Well, I'll get it."

465
00:32:58,226 --> 00:33:03,981
He said, "No, it's a cross to the window.
I want it more precise than it is now."

466
00:33:04,524 --> 00:33:09,236
"What do you mean, like going around
a chair, or picking up a teapot or what?"

467
00:33:09,321 --> 00:33:12,031
He said,
"Just..." I said, "We'll get it, I..."

468
00:33:12,115 --> 00:33:15,451
He said,
"Well, Al..." I said, "Well, it's May."

469
00:33:15,535 --> 00:33:21,290
He said, "The clock is ticking,"
which I'm sure you've heard many times.

470
00:33:21,375 --> 00:33:25,002
Did he ever connect you back
to From Here to Eternity?

471
00:33:25,087 --> 00:33:30,633
We had lunch one day
with him and his friend.

472
00:33:31,968 --> 00:33:38,182
And I said, "Do you remember
From Here to Eternity?"

473
00:33:38,266 --> 00:33:41,477
And I mentioned the scene,
and I said, "That's me, Fred."

474
00:33:41,561 --> 00:33:43,938
I remember. And he was pleased.

475
00:33:44,022 --> 00:33:47,233
The next day, he gave me
a photograph of himself

476
00:33:47,317 --> 00:33:50,695
and Burt Lancaster and Monty Clift.

477
00:33:50,821 --> 00:33:54,240
They signed it. I still have it on my wall.

478
00:33:55,867 --> 00:34:01,831
I noticed the scene that's coming up here
was highly controversial at the time.

479
00:34:05,210 --> 00:34:11,549
And I think, was it the Breen Office,
it was the censorship of the day,

480
00:34:12,759 --> 00:34:19,640
insisted that Deborah Kerr
wear a skirt over her bathing suit.

481
00:34:19,975 --> 00:34:25,563
They were insistent that
they not touch in a certain way.

482
00:34:26,815 --> 00:34:30,484
It's still one of the most
romantic scenes in film.

483
00:34:30,986 --> 00:34:35,698
I think what they found erotic
and objectionable was the water

484
00:34:35,824 --> 00:34:37,074
in that particular scene.

485
00:34:37,159 --> 00:34:38,451
Rolling up over them.

486
00:34:38,535 --> 00:34:41,036
They wanted some cuts made.

487
00:34:43,248 --> 00:34:46,625
There were certain angles that
my father was not allowed to shoot

488
00:34:46,710 --> 00:34:49,170
because of censorship at the time.

489
00:34:49,463 --> 00:34:55,176
It's a scene that caused a big flap
in its day, as I remember.

490
00:34:56,887 --> 00:35:01,557
Must have been phone calls every day
from Hollywood to Honolulu,

491
00:35:01,725 --> 00:35:04,810
with your father ignoring most of them.

492
00:35:04,936 --> 00:35:07,438
Ignoring everything he could.

493
00:35:07,522 --> 00:35:11,525
But sometimes there was too much pressure
and he had to give in.

494
00:35:13,862 --> 00:35:16,071
Let's go up to Mrs Kipfer's parlour
and sit there.

495
00:35:17,199 --> 00:35:21,202
- She was really wonderful.
- Donna Reed was great.

496
00:35:22,204 --> 00:35:27,875
I think up to this time, she'd done
mainly roles of starlets and stuff.

497
00:35:28,543 --> 00:35:33,297
- Was she on television already or...
- I don't think so.

498
00:35:33,381 --> 00:35:36,717
I think she was just
a contract player at Columbia.

499
00:35:37,886 --> 00:35:44,767
The water, this part is what the Breen Office,
they objected to this.

500
00:35:45,519 --> 00:35:47,686
The water rushing in.

501
00:35:47,771 --> 00:35:50,481
- Oh, boy.
- But it stayed in.

502
00:35:50,565 --> 00:35:52,858
And then running after her.

503
00:35:52,943 --> 00:35:58,405
And then for years, this was one of the most
famous love scenes ever shot, I think.

504
00:35:59,950 --> 00:36:04,411
They're so mature, these two people.
It made it so much more exciting

505
00:36:04,496 --> 00:36:07,748
that they weren't just young kids.

506
00:36:08,959 --> 00:36:13,003
There's an elegance about the way it's shot.
It's the utter precision, too.

507
00:36:16,174 --> 00:36:19,051
Black and white does so much
for you, though. Doesn't it?

508
00:36:19,135 --> 00:36:22,513
- If he did that in colour, wouldn't you lose...
- A lot.

509
00:36:24,182 --> 00:36:28,352
Because it makes it very specific
and you're focused in on these two.

510
00:36:28,436 --> 00:36:31,438
- How many men do you think there've been?
- I wouldn't know.

511
00:36:31,565 --> 00:36:33,440
Can't you give me a rough estimate?

512
00:36:33,525 --> 00:36:39,446
I saw your father when he was here last time.
What's that? 15 years ago?

513
00:36:39,614 --> 00:36:42,366
- No, when was he here last?
- '92.

514
00:36:42,492 --> 00:36:47,705
'92, yeah. We had lunch together.
It was a nice time.

515
00:36:48,123 --> 00:36:53,294
Yeah, he died in '97, so it's the last trip
he made to Los Angeles.

516
00:36:54,254 --> 00:36:56,839
The year before he died,
I was in London with my granddaughter.

517
00:36:56,923 --> 00:36:58,257
I took her for a trip.

518
00:36:58,341 --> 00:37:00,634
We went and tried to find his...

519
00:37:00,719 --> 00:37:02,720
We went over to...

520
00:37:02,804 --> 00:37:05,014
- What's the street he was on?
- Mount Street.

521
00:37:05,098 --> 00:37:09,059
Mount Street. But nobody was there.

522
00:37:09,144 --> 00:37:11,270
- 98 Mount Street?
- 98, yeah.

523
00:37:11,354 --> 00:37:13,606
He was there,
but probably wasn't answering.

524
00:37:13,690 --> 00:37:15,190
I think that's right.

525
00:37:15,275 --> 00:37:17,610
Yeah. Because he became very deaf.

526
00:37:17,694 --> 00:37:20,404
That's too bad.

527
00:37:20,488 --> 00:37:22,406
Which he was able to use as a weapon,

528
00:37:22,490 --> 00:37:25,409
because he basically heard
anything he wanted to hear.

529
00:37:25,493 --> 00:37:28,996
But he would pretend that
he hadn't heard anything.

530
00:37:29,205 --> 00:37:31,206
I should have sent him a note.

531
00:37:32,500 --> 00:37:39,256
During Julia,
I had the apartment next door,

532
00:37:40,216 --> 00:37:45,012
up above the chicken store.
I think there was a bakery or a butcher.

533
00:37:46,848 --> 00:37:49,600
We had two scripts.

534
00:37:52,354 --> 00:37:57,107
We had the red script, which was my script,
and there was your father's script,

535
00:37:57,233 --> 00:38:00,402
which had certain changes in it
that we fought.

536
00:38:00,487 --> 00:38:05,491
We used to have a big sign up
on the wall in our office,

537
00:38:05,617 --> 00:38:08,535
and it said, "Better red than Fred."

538
00:38:10,664 --> 00:38:16,251
We had a good time, though.
I learned a lot from your father.

539
00:38:19,881 --> 00:38:23,300
I'd only been married to Dana two years
when I found out he was cheating.

540
00:38:23,385 --> 00:38:27,012
This looks like it was shot late in the day.

541
00:38:27,097 --> 00:38:29,390
I thought I had something to hope for.

542
00:38:29,474 --> 00:38:32,726
I was almost happy
the night the pains began.

543
00:38:32,978 --> 00:38:36,313
I think this scene still holds up
after all these years.

544
00:38:36,398 --> 00:38:38,482
It's very sensual, don't you think?

545
00:38:39,067 --> 00:38:42,069
She's a knockout.

546
00:38:42,278 --> 00:38:45,197
He was drunk when he came in at 5:00 a.m.

547
00:38:45,281 --> 00:38:46,865
He was great.

548
00:38:48,618 --> 00:38:51,245
Did he win an Oscar,
or did she win an Oscar?

549
00:38:51,329 --> 00:38:55,582
No, they were both nominated.
Donna Reed and Frank Sinatra did.

550
00:38:55,750 --> 00:39:02,214
I think the picture was nominated
for 13 and won eight Academy Awards.

551
00:39:02,340 --> 00:39:09,221
My father did win and Taradash won,
and the picture won and editing.

552
00:39:10,390 --> 00:39:12,683
But in the way this is shot,

553
00:39:12,767 --> 00:39:18,981
this very much goes back to his beginning
and his influences with Flaherty.

554
00:39:19,107 --> 00:39:20,482
It's very precise.

555
00:39:20,567 --> 00:39:25,362
He also worked with a great man,
Paul Strand, who was a still photographer.

556
00:39:25,447 --> 00:39:27,865
He was also a cinematographer.

557
00:39:29,617 --> 00:39:31,035
There's a real elegance

558
00:39:31,119 --> 00:39:36,582
to how he composed his shots
and a real precision to it.

559
00:39:36,791 --> 00:39:39,418
Did your father make some documentaries?

560
00:39:39,502 --> 00:39:43,047
He made one and he actually won
an Academy Award for it.

561
00:39:43,131 --> 00:39:47,342
It was for orthopaedic hospitals.
It was a charity thing.

562
00:39:49,971 --> 00:39:54,516
But no, he wanted to, and he was dying
to work with Flaherty,

563
00:39:54,601 --> 00:39:59,063
but he wound up spending six months
in Berlin drinking beer with Flaherty

564
00:39:59,147 --> 00:40:04,109
and not making anything.
But he did learn a lot from him.

565
00:40:05,945 --> 00:40:10,032
Look at her. Look at that arm.

566
00:40:11,826 --> 00:40:15,829
In my father's direction,
everything is thought out.

567
00:40:15,955 --> 00:40:18,832
It was always very precise.

568
00:40:18,917 --> 00:40:23,962
Nothing was ever left to chance,
in terms of the framing, the staging.

569
00:40:26,341 --> 00:40:30,928
He was a big believer in preparation.
He never did wing it.

570
00:40:31,012 --> 00:40:32,888
Tell me about it.

571
00:40:34,808 --> 00:40:38,435
But there was a security in that, too,
when you worked with him.

572
00:40:38,520 --> 00:40:44,691
You wrote, and you placed something
on a page and it was agreed on.

573
00:40:44,943 --> 00:40:49,446
And you felt that what
you were going to do next,

574
00:40:49,656 --> 00:40:54,910
whatever you were going to do,
was going to be given some credibility.

575
00:40:55,078 --> 00:40:59,039
You weren't going to have to worry about it
being tampered with all the time.

576
00:40:59,165 --> 00:41:00,374
Right.

577
00:41:00,959 --> 00:41:06,338
There's a scene that's going
to be coming up later with Sinatra,

578
00:41:06,506 --> 00:41:09,299
where he is arrested and is resisting arrest.

579
00:41:09,384 --> 00:41:13,387
I think it was the last night of shooting.

580
00:41:14,889 --> 00:41:19,726
Harry Cohn had come over
and was not coming on the set,

581
00:41:19,811 --> 00:41:23,397
but was getting reports back as
to how everything was going.

582
00:41:23,481 --> 00:41:25,899
There weren't really any problems.

583
00:41:26,025 --> 00:41:31,280
They were delighted with dailies
and everything was going really well.

584
00:41:32,490 --> 00:41:37,828
But there was some concern about the scene
that my father had staged that afternoon

585
00:41:37,912 --> 00:41:44,418
that they were going to shoot at night, where
Maggio is standing up, resisting arrest.

586
00:41:44,502 --> 00:41:49,923
The Army complained to Cohn
and said they didn't want him to resist.

587
00:41:50,049 --> 00:41:52,467
They just wanted him to be arrested.

588
00:41:52,552 --> 00:41:55,637
That night, while they were
shooting the scene,

589
00:41:55,722 --> 00:42:00,893
Cohn came on the set
with the commandant of the base

590
00:42:01,436 --> 00:42:03,979
to watch the shooting.

591
00:42:05,607 --> 00:42:10,110
They started to shoot
as they had staged the scene.

592
00:42:10,695 --> 00:42:16,491
Cohn went to my father and said, "Maggio
has to sit down, not stand up in the scene."

593
00:42:17,660 --> 00:42:20,120
Contrary to my father's character

594
00:42:20,205 --> 00:42:22,873
and contrary to everything
he had done before,

595
00:42:22,957 --> 00:42:24,875
he said, "Yes, okay."

596
00:42:26,127 --> 00:42:31,089
I think this caused a rift
with Sinatra and my father

597
00:42:31,174 --> 00:42:34,218
that never healed, really.

598
00:42:35,136 --> 00:42:42,017
But my father, according to him, did this
because the Army insisted on it,

599
00:42:42,143 --> 00:42:46,605
and he felt that he had pushed it to the wall,

600
00:42:46,689 --> 00:42:50,525
and he wasn't going to get them to bend,

601
00:42:50,610 --> 00:42:56,698
so he just gave up on that point
and had Maggio sit down in the scene,

602
00:42:57,492 --> 00:43:00,953
which, apparently,
Sinatra was very upset about.

603
00:43:01,287 --> 00:43:04,790
...and he must have been set
pretty flat on his feet...

604
00:43:04,874 --> 00:43:09,962
I liked him sitting down. It's fine.
Maybe your father knew that, too.

605
00:43:10,046 --> 00:43:14,925
Maybe he thought, "That's not a bad idea.
I'll act as if I'm giving him something."

606
00:43:15,009 --> 00:43:18,220
I think in Sinatra's mind,

607
00:43:18,304 --> 00:43:25,227
he lost respect for my father
for not standing up for himself.

608
00:43:33,319 --> 00:43:37,864
You said that Clift was
a good friend of your family's?

609
00:43:38,199 --> 00:43:42,577
- You spent a lot of time with him socially?
- Well, we went back...

610
00:43:42,745 --> 00:43:46,123
Clift did, I think, his first picture,

611
00:43:46,207 --> 00:43:49,584
I can't remember if it was before Red River
or right after,

612
00:43:49,752 --> 00:43:52,796
but he got the lead in
a picture called The Search

613
00:43:52,880 --> 00:43:57,551
that my father did in Germany
right after World War II,

614
00:43:57,969 --> 00:44:01,471
and did it very much as a documentary.

615
00:44:04,058 --> 00:44:09,229
And Clift became a very close family friend,

616
00:44:09,814 --> 00:44:12,149
including a friend to me.

617
00:44:12,317 --> 00:44:15,235
He used to come
and play with me all the time.

618
00:44:15,737 --> 00:44:18,822
He had his agent send me birthday presents.

619
00:44:18,906 --> 00:44:20,449
His agent was Lew Wasserman,

620
00:44:20,533 --> 00:44:24,953
so he'd send Lew Wasserman out
to buy me a birthday gift.

621
00:44:26,622 --> 00:44:31,626
- How old were you now?
- When we first met Clift, I was seven or six.

622
00:44:32,337 --> 00:44:35,922
During the making of From Here to Eternity,
I was 13.

623
00:44:37,300 --> 00:44:44,097
But Clift, until his death,
was a close family friend to all of us.

624
00:44:51,397 --> 00:44:55,108
I remember taking little walks around
that beach with your mother.

625
00:44:55,193 --> 00:44:56,693
- Really?
- Yeah.

626
00:44:56,778 --> 00:44:58,320
I don't know why.

627
00:44:58,613 --> 00:45:02,407
I found myself once walking with Fred's wife.

628
00:45:02,492 --> 00:45:04,326
Really? That's funny.

629
00:45:05,119 --> 00:45:07,120
All right, that's enough.

630
00:45:19,634 --> 00:45:23,095
Okay, Prewitt, bury it.

631
00:45:31,646 --> 00:45:35,941
Clift looks in great shape there.
He does look like a middleweight.

632
00:45:36,025 --> 00:45:38,026
Yeah, absolutely.

633
00:45:41,197 --> 00:45:44,366
I used to go and watch him
with Mushy Callahan.

634
00:45:44,492 --> 00:45:49,913
I used to go and watch them training.
It was kind of fun.

635
00:45:50,206 --> 00:45:53,250
So much my pockets is sore

636
00:45:53,334 --> 00:45:55,794
Oh, my pockets is sore

637
00:45:55,878 --> 00:45:57,838
Yeah, that a boy!

638
00:45:57,922 --> 00:46:00,841
More dough than I can use

639
00:46:00,925 --> 00:46:04,094
Reenlistment blues

640
00:46:04,178 --> 00:46:05,429
Sing it, boys!

641
00:46:21,195 --> 00:46:22,404
Time!

642
00:46:33,583 --> 00:46:40,213
My father, being very precise in his thinking,

643
00:46:40,298 --> 00:46:43,300
in the way that he shoots
and the way that he prepares,

644
00:46:45,553 --> 00:46:49,389
contrary to that,
he was also a great risk-taker,

645
00:46:49,474 --> 00:46:52,517
as Alvin was talking about with Vanessa.

646
00:46:53,603 --> 00:46:59,649
And possibly throwing the best person
for the part out of the movie

647
00:47:00,693 --> 00:47:04,404
just because she resisted some changes.

648
00:47:05,781 --> 00:47:11,036
Anyway, my father,
right after From Here to Eternity,

649
00:47:11,245 --> 00:47:14,915
was riding high, extremely successful.

650
00:47:15,666 --> 00:47:19,002
He went out and did something
that he'd never done before,

651
00:47:19,086 --> 00:47:20,462
which is, bought a new car.

652
00:47:20,546 --> 00:47:27,385
It was this fancy Jaguar that he picked up
in Italy for some reason.

653
00:47:29,096 --> 00:47:31,765
He said to me, "Let's go for a ride."

654
00:47:31,849 --> 00:47:36,394
We were in Rome
and he loved to drive really fast.

655
00:47:36,521 --> 00:47:38,688
He was actually a reckless driver.

656
00:47:38,814 --> 00:47:40,440
We were approaching Switzerland

657
00:47:40,525 --> 00:47:45,362
at about 100 miles an hour
in this fancy Mark VII Jaguar.

658
00:47:45,446 --> 00:47:49,699
There was a gypsy caravan going
into a tunnel ahead of us,

659
00:47:49,867 --> 00:47:52,452
and there were two choices,

660
00:47:52,620 --> 00:47:57,082
either slow down and go through the tunnel
behind the horse-drawn caravan,

661
00:47:57,250 --> 00:48:00,460
or try to pass them in the tunnel.

662
00:48:00,878 --> 00:48:06,132
The car was very big
and the caravan overhung the road.

663
00:48:06,217 --> 00:48:10,971
It didn't look like we were all going to fit.
But he decided to gun it.

664
00:48:12,056 --> 00:48:16,393
So he passed the caravan
on the wrong side of the road in the tunnel

665
00:48:18,646 --> 00:48:21,856
with sparks coming off the driver's side,

666
00:48:21,983 --> 00:48:26,069
because he kept hitting the tunnel wall
all the way through.

667
00:48:26,195 --> 00:48:29,906
And sparks were flying off his side,

668
00:48:29,991 --> 00:48:35,328
and we just kept on going straight through
the tunnel and got to the other side.

669
00:48:37,081 --> 00:48:40,834
He had been, with me,
very precise getting into the car,

670
00:48:41,002 --> 00:48:45,422
not to put my fingerprints on the glass,
and not to touch the seat

671
00:48:45,506 --> 00:48:48,883
and not to touch the wood
and all of these things,

672
00:48:49,135 --> 00:48:52,053
and to be very careful
because it was brand new.

673
00:48:52,138 --> 00:48:56,266
Now, essentially, the whole left side
of the car had been sheared off.

674
00:48:56,350 --> 00:49:00,520
He completely played it
like nothing had happened.

675
00:49:01,647 --> 00:49:06,318
We got out of the tunnel, past the caravan.
We were still going 100 miles an hour.

676
00:49:06,485 --> 00:49:10,030
I think we stopped
someplace in Italy for lunch.

677
00:49:10,698 --> 00:49:13,533
We just pulled to a stop and he said,

678
00:49:13,701 --> 00:49:16,202
"Excuse me, but I think
I'd better get out your side.

679
00:49:16,287 --> 00:49:19,039
"There's something wrong with my door."

680
00:49:20,207 --> 00:49:25,545
That's very much how my father was,

681
00:49:25,713 --> 00:49:28,465
not only in life, but in his work.

682
00:49:28,549 --> 00:49:34,346
There was definitely this dichotomy
where he was extremely precise,

683
00:49:34,513 --> 00:49:41,144
but he was also willing to throw it
all away at any time for a principle.

684
00:49:41,729 --> 00:49:43,688
And a good story.

685
00:49:46,942 --> 00:49:50,612
Well, good for him. I'll buy that.

686
00:49:50,696 --> 00:49:54,699
I would have taken a long time
and been behind that cart.

