00:51:08,649 --> 00:51:13,111
I remember he considered John Ford
a mentor, in a way,

703
00:51:13,195 --> 00:51:15,488
and he very much admired his work.

704
00:51:16,198 --> 00:51:19,743
Ford said to him about his earlier work,
he said,

705
00:51:19,827 --> 00:51:24,581
"You know, kid, you've got potential,
but you move the camera too much.

706
00:51:25,291 --> 00:51:28,835
"Just remember the camera
is an information booth

707
00:51:28,919 --> 00:51:31,254
"and let the people come to you."

708
00:51:31,338 --> 00:51:34,090
I think that's something
that stuck with my father, too.

709
00:51:34,175 --> 00:51:38,094
I've watched him
and what I found was that he...

710
00:51:38,179 --> 00:51:41,514
And then I started doing it in writing, too.

711
00:51:43,225 --> 00:51:47,729
He doesn't move in on faces.

712
00:51:48,522 --> 00:51:55,528
He cuts closer and cuts closer,
but there's never that zooming in.

713
00:51:58,365 --> 00:52:00,742
Because I don't think
that's how stories are told, anyway.

714
00:52:00,868 --> 00:52:07,332
You always tell a story... A story's like a...

715
00:52:08,918 --> 00:52:15,799
A movie's like a joke. Like you tell a joke,
that's how you tell a movie, a story.

716
00:52:16,133 --> 00:52:21,721
So this happened, two guys came into a bar.
They stood in front of the bartender.

717
00:52:21,847 --> 00:52:26,559
An elephant walked in the door.
You know, it's all very quick, very precise.

718
00:52:26,852 --> 00:52:30,980
Dreams are also, I think, very much...

719
00:52:31,065 --> 00:52:35,819
I write when I think about cutting,
moving a story along,

720
00:52:35,903 --> 00:52:40,073
I think about, "Does it work in a dream?
Does it work in a joke?"

721
00:52:40,241 --> 00:52:43,243
When you tell a tale... And your father...

722
00:52:43,786 --> 00:52:48,081
I don't know if this applies
to what I'm talking about with your father,

723
00:52:48,207 --> 00:52:51,709
but if you watch, you don't see
a lot of camera movement.

724
00:52:51,794 --> 00:52:56,422
You don't see a lot of... God.
Zooming in and out.

725
00:52:56,549 --> 00:52:58,216
Panning, very little panning.

726
00:52:58,300 --> 00:53:02,095
No, he was a very good editor

727
00:53:02,179 --> 00:53:07,267
and relied on good editors,
such as Walter Murch

728
00:53:07,351 --> 00:53:12,605
and a lot of people that he worked with
to really let them do their job.

729
00:53:15,109 --> 00:53:21,698
- Murch was very helpful on Julia.
- I'm sure he was.

730
00:53:21,782 --> 00:53:24,534
But he definitely listened to the editors,

731
00:53:24,618 --> 00:53:27,120
and he gave them the respect
that they're due.

732
00:53:28,122 --> 00:53:31,416
Editing was very important to him.

733
00:53:31,500 --> 00:53:33,251
He was an editor, wasn't he?

734
00:53:33,335 --> 00:53:36,838
He began as an assistant
cameraman in Berlin.

735
00:53:36,922 --> 00:53:41,217
He worked with Billy Wilder
on his first movie.

736
00:53:41,343 --> 00:53:46,139
He came to Hollywood,
hoping to break in as a cameraman.

737
00:53:46,557 --> 00:53:51,728
His first job was as an extra as a German
lieutenant on All Quiet on the Western Front.

738
00:53:51,812 --> 00:53:53,313
Really?

739
00:53:54,273 --> 00:53:58,860
He was told by the first assistant director
to do something and he said no.

740
00:53:58,986 --> 00:54:02,113
He got fired, which is typical of him.

741
00:54:02,197 --> 00:54:04,073
Glad he was acting.

742
00:54:09,872 --> 00:54:12,916
But in terms of his camera set-ups,

743
00:54:13,042 --> 00:54:20,006
he's always doing it being terribly aware
of how he's going to edit the picture.

744
00:54:22,468 --> 00:54:24,928
He also started in the shorts department,

745
00:54:26,555 --> 00:54:30,350
so he learned how to tell a story,
say of George Washington,

746
00:54:30,434 --> 00:54:34,771
80 years of George Washington
Carver's life in 10 minutes.

747
00:54:34,897 --> 00:54:40,652
So there was always this economy
to his style.

748
00:54:42,696 --> 00:54:46,741
He always knew
where he was going to go with the material.

749
00:54:46,825 --> 00:54:50,495
Also, in these days, in the '50s,

750
00:54:50,579 --> 00:54:57,126
people like Harry Cohn
did interfere with editing a lot,

751
00:54:57,336 --> 00:55:02,215
the process, and they did have final cut
and the directors didn't.

752
00:55:02,508 --> 00:55:05,635
In the case of From Here to Eternity,

753
00:55:05,719 --> 00:55:10,181
I think they shot it in the spring of '53,

754
00:55:10,265 --> 00:55:15,687
and they had it edited by June

755
00:55:15,771 --> 00:55:17,188
and in the theatres by August.

756
00:55:17,272 --> 00:55:19,941
So it's a very fast schedule.

757
00:55:22,611 --> 00:55:27,573
They didn't give my father much time
to edit the movie.

758
00:55:27,658 --> 00:55:31,577
Cohn came right in and took it over
and made his changes,

759
00:55:31,662 --> 00:55:36,249
and my father had to fight tooth and nail
for what he believed in with Cohn.

760
00:55:38,002 --> 00:55:43,965
The picture was released in August
in the biggest theatre on Broadway,

761
00:55:45,092 --> 00:55:47,635
which was not air-conditioned.

762
00:55:49,054 --> 00:55:53,474
It was regarded as
a very foolish move by many,

763
00:55:53,600 --> 00:55:56,352
but Cohn took full responsibility for it.

764
00:55:56,437 --> 00:55:59,689
They didn't do a press preview
for the picture.

765
00:55:59,773 --> 00:56:01,607
They just released it.

766
00:56:01,775 --> 00:56:04,736
On the first night at midnight,

767
00:56:04,820 --> 00:56:09,032
Marlene Dietrich called my father,
who he didn't know that well,

768
00:56:09,158 --> 00:56:15,121
and said there's lines around the block
and they've added a 1:00 show.

769
00:56:15,497 --> 00:56:18,499
Then everybody knew
it was going to be a big hit.

770
00:56:18,625 --> 00:56:20,043
Great.

771
00:56:21,670 --> 00:56:24,714
They opened it here at the Pantages Theater.

772
00:56:24,965 --> 00:56:28,843
I went back after my week or so
on this movie.

773
00:56:29,136 --> 00:56:34,140
I went back to selling advertising
at Daily Variety.

774
00:56:34,224 --> 00:56:39,771
They opened the movie five months later,
whenever it was, six months later,

775
00:56:41,648 --> 00:56:46,194
and I went to the premiere by myself, I think.

776
00:56:46,820 --> 00:56:53,534
And sat there, somehow I got in
and watched this movie.

777
00:56:53,660 --> 00:56:59,916
Suddenly there I was,
this amazing full close-up

778
00:57:00,125 --> 00:57:03,461
on the Pantages movie house screen.

779
00:57:04,671 --> 00:57:06,839
It must have been a thrill.

780
00:57:06,965 --> 00:57:10,510
I didn't know if it was a thrill
or embarrassing, I couldn't tell.

781
00:57:10,594 --> 00:57:13,262
It's like listening to your own voice.

782
00:57:13,806 --> 00:57:16,682
That scene will be coming up
here in a minute.

783
00:57:18,519 --> 00:57:23,356
But there was definitely a feeling
about this movie in pre-production

784
00:57:23,440 --> 00:57:25,900
that it was a great script and a great project.

785
00:57:25,984 --> 00:57:28,986
I remember the opening night,
the premiere there.

786
00:57:29,071 --> 00:57:31,948
It was a thrilling night.

787
00:57:32,074 --> 00:57:36,994
Everybody just couldn't get over it.

788
00:57:37,913 --> 00:57:40,164
My own personal recollection,

789
00:57:40,249 --> 00:57:44,127
I had just been for the summer
touring Europe

790
00:57:44,378 --> 00:57:46,546
with some people from my school

791
00:57:46,630 --> 00:57:49,590
and met my father in New York
just as the picture...

792
00:57:49,716 --> 00:57:53,803
I think it was in its first week,
I forget the theatre, on Broadway.

793
00:57:54,012 --> 00:57:58,891
He said to me, "Do you want to go see
my latest picture, From Here to Eternity?"

794
00:57:59,017 --> 00:58:02,270
And I said, "Sure, I'd be thrilled."

795
00:58:02,354 --> 00:58:08,067
It was the first time he'd allowed me to see
one of his pictures, other than High Noon.

796
00:58:09,319 --> 00:58:12,405
So we went to the theatre.

797
00:58:12,739 --> 00:58:17,952
It was a really hot day, and we got close
and there was this huge long line

798
00:58:18,036 --> 00:58:20,329
that went all the way around the block.

799
00:58:20,414 --> 00:58:22,748
We got right up to the front door.

800
00:58:22,916 --> 00:58:26,794
He talked to somebody there
and they let us right in.

801
00:58:27,129 --> 00:58:30,381
I was completely impressed.

802
00:58:30,465 --> 00:58:33,926
The long line was for the next show.

803
00:58:34,011 --> 00:58:38,556
There was a show in progress,
so they were in line waiting for two hours.

804
00:58:39,474 --> 00:58:42,143
We went in and sat down.

805
00:58:42,227 --> 00:58:46,397
It was a theatre that held 2,000 people.
It was a big deal.

806
00:58:47,107 --> 00:58:50,860
That was the first moment
that I knew my father had made it.

807
00:58:50,944 --> 00:58:54,113
Because prior to that,
he was an art-house director,

808
00:58:54,198 --> 00:58:59,118
and we lived in a small house
and drove an old car.

809
00:58:59,286 --> 00:59:01,287
This was his big moment.

810
00:59:01,413 --> 00:59:06,417
Great. He shared it. Beautiful.
Big moment in your life.

811
00:59:08,295 --> 00:59:10,296
I'll meet you at the Kalakaua, later.

812
00:59:16,803 --> 00:59:20,139
- There's Bob Wilke.
- There's Bob Wilke.

813
00:59:20,515 --> 00:59:22,308
Maggio, get ready for guard.

814
00:59:22,684 --> 00:59:24,101
Campaign hat, cartridge belt and weapon.

