00:59:24,186 --> 00:59:26,437
He was also in High Noon, actually.

816
00:59:26,521 --> 00:59:28,856
- Was he one of the three guys?
- Yeah.

817
00:59:28,941 --> 00:59:31,150
Not any more. Anderson's sick.
You're on guard.

818
00:59:31,235 --> 00:59:32,568
I just had guard yesterday.

819
00:59:32,653 --> 00:59:34,445
That was a great film.

820
00:59:34,529 --> 00:59:37,156
You should've gotten dressed faster.

821
00:59:44,665 --> 00:59:47,750
I sure never figured
in your giving me the runaround.

822
00:59:47,834 --> 00:59:50,795
- They didn't even want to let me in this place.
- We're mobbed, that's why.

823
00:59:51,588 --> 00:59:54,632
Talking about editing,

824
00:59:56,927 --> 01:00:00,429
the way things worked in 1953,

825
01:00:00,514 --> 01:00:04,433
Harry Cohn had the final cut.

826
01:00:06,853 --> 01:00:11,399
A lot of the things that the directors
of those days did in self-defence

827
01:00:11,483 --> 01:00:16,195
was what they used to call camera-cutting,

828
01:00:16,280 --> 01:00:23,244
and not give what they called "the
front office" enough coverage to work with,

829
01:00:23,370 --> 01:00:27,373
so that a scene could only be cut in one way.

830
01:00:27,457 --> 01:00:30,459
And this was a trick
my father learned early on

831
01:00:30,544 --> 01:00:36,716
and utilised in most of his movies up to
this point, including From Here to Eternity.

832
01:00:38,135 --> 01:00:42,638
So I think a lot of that
was why he was so precise.

833
01:00:44,599 --> 01:00:49,729
It was just a way to protect himself
and protect his vision of the movie.

834
01:00:53,066 --> 01:00:55,901
As I think I said before, the picture

835
01:00:58,071 --> 01:01:03,117
was made quite quickly, in today's terms.

836
01:01:03,201 --> 01:01:05,411
So it was made in eight weeks.

837
01:01:07,164 --> 01:01:12,418
The cutting period was only about
two months before they went to a preview.

838
01:01:15,088 --> 01:01:19,925
I think that they found in the first preview
that they were going to have a monstrous hit,

839
01:01:20,927 --> 01:01:24,680
because they utilised something
that was new for the time.

840
01:01:24,765 --> 01:01:31,228
They wired every seat in the preview theatre,

841
01:01:31,313 --> 01:01:35,608
and they were able to get
the response of everybody

842
01:01:35,692 --> 01:01:38,527
to each particular scene
at any given moment.

843
01:01:38,612 --> 01:01:41,947
And apparently, Harry Cohn

844
01:01:42,032 --> 01:01:46,035
came out with a 25-foot-long roll of paper

845
01:01:46,119 --> 01:01:51,791
with a graph that showed everybody's
reaction to everything in the picture,

846
01:01:51,875 --> 01:01:56,796
and came screaming down the aisles
and saying, "We have a hit! We have a hit!"

847
01:01:56,880 --> 01:01:59,715
And I don't believe
they ever previewed the picture again.

848
01:01:59,800 --> 01:02:03,052
And they just decided to release it in August.

849
01:02:03,136 --> 01:02:06,639
So from inception to release,

850
01:02:08,642 --> 01:02:12,561
it was less than a year,
which was very fast.

851
01:02:14,606 --> 01:02:16,732
See, I'm just lucky getting in town.

852
01:02:16,817 --> 01:02:20,111
- Topkick gave me a break.
- They still pouring it on?

853
01:02:20,195 --> 01:02:22,988
Holmes and those others,
they really got me on the edge.

854
01:02:23,073 --> 01:02:26,575
- Gee, you must hate the army.
