01:06:27,567 --> 01:06:33,238
I think this is the scene coming up
that was the one I was talking about earlier.

916
01:06:33,490 --> 01:06:35,199
Come and get me, you guys!

917
01:06:35,283 --> 01:06:37,284
Here I am!

918
01:06:41,414 --> 01:06:45,000
Is that the best you can do?
I bet you guys eat Wheaties!

919
01:06:53,677 --> 01:06:57,846
Harry Bellaver, he was in Naked City.
I used to write Naked City's...

920
01:06:57,931 --> 01:06:58,889
Television.

921
01:06:58,973 --> 01:07:01,100
- Which one is he?
- He's sitting on the desk in the...

922
01:07:03,436 --> 01:07:07,022
He's one of the three cops in Naked City.

923
01:07:10,860 --> 01:07:15,698
So many of these actors
have had such careers that...

924
01:07:15,782 --> 01:07:17,282
There's Jack Warden.

925
01:07:18,535 --> 01:07:21,453
He was also another one up for the captain.

926
01:07:21,538 --> 01:07:23,288
- Jack Warden was?
- Yeah.

927
01:07:27,836 --> 01:07:30,921
Go on and shoot some pool.
Any word comes through, I'll let you know.

928
01:07:33,967 --> 01:07:36,468
Don Dubbins, over there on the left.

929
01:07:38,054 --> 01:07:40,848
He'd just gotten married, I think, when...

930
01:07:43,476 --> 01:07:46,145
See, going back to what I was saying earlier

931
01:07:46,229 --> 01:07:50,899
about my father's
being influenced by documentaries,

932
01:07:50,984 --> 01:07:55,571
you can see how he used practical locations.

933
01:07:57,490 --> 01:07:59,742
He used very few sets.

934
01:07:59,826 --> 01:08:04,413
And this is something
that's commonplace now, but in those days,

935
01:08:05,665 --> 01:08:07,374
it was rarely done.

936
01:08:08,668 --> 01:08:11,837
It's another thing he utilised,
practical locations.

937
01:08:11,921 --> 01:08:15,007
It was very important to him
to get a real look.

938
01:08:23,600 --> 01:08:27,686
There was, I think, about another 20 minutes
in the original script

939
01:08:27,771 --> 01:08:33,275
where Sinatra is beat up in jail.

940
01:08:33,359 --> 01:08:38,697
And that was one of the cuts
that the Army insisted upon.

941
01:08:40,116 --> 01:08:44,328
And Taradash and my father
gladly agreed to it,

942
01:08:44,412 --> 01:08:47,456
because they thought
the movie was too long, anyway.

943
01:08:49,459 --> 01:08:53,921
So all you saw there was him pick up the
baton, and that's all you really need to see.

944
01:08:54,005 --> 01:08:56,381
And I tell about it, in a minute.

945
01:08:56,591 --> 01:08:59,843
You can use it any time you want to,
even when I'm not here.

946
01:09:09,312 --> 01:09:10,896
- Hi.
- Hi.

947
01:09:11,064 --> 01:09:13,732
This is Prew, the soldier I told you about.

948
01:09:14,734 --> 01:09:19,404
It's a simple character,
simple girl, pretty girl.

949
01:09:19,489 --> 01:09:22,699
I think it's interesting
how they made this work.

950
01:09:24,828 --> 01:09:28,580
Even though she's supposed to be
a prostitute, they managed to make...

951
01:09:28,665 --> 01:09:30,666
- But it still worked, didn't it?
- It still somehow worked.

952
01:09:30,750 --> 01:09:34,837
- It was right on the cusp, almost.
- Yeah.

953
01:09:34,921 --> 01:09:39,508
And there's not a lot of set dressing,
you notice, on all of his shots.

954
01:09:40,426 --> 01:09:43,846
It's the people
that seem to be more important than...

955
01:09:45,348 --> 01:09:46,431
In terms of... What do you mean?

956
01:09:46,516 --> 01:09:49,977
In all the scenes,
there's something very clean about...

957
01:09:51,020 --> 01:09:55,023
His framing
is very precise and well thought out.

958
01:10:07,495 --> 01:10:09,454
You okay?

959
01:10:12,792 --> 01:10:14,835
Perfect couple.

960
01:10:23,887 --> 01:10:27,139
The cameraman won an Academy Award
for this movie, too.

961
01:10:27,223 --> 01:10:28,390
Burnie Guffey.

962
01:10:28,474 --> 01:10:31,101
- Lighting is so great, isn't it?
- Yeah.

963
01:10:32,145 --> 01:10:33,604
Look at that.

964
01:11:02,050 --> 01:11:05,177
Let's get out of here. Don't look around.

965
01:11:07,931 --> 01:11:10,140
So interesting, Ernie Borgnine

966
01:11:10,224 --> 01:11:15,771
going from Marty, the sweet butcher boy,

967
01:11:16,439 --> 01:11:19,858
to the totally bad...

968
01:11:19,943 --> 01:11:22,110
To Fatso.

969
01:11:22,195 --> 01:11:24,529
I think he was a marvellous villain.

970
01:11:24,614 --> 01:11:26,073
He was great.

971
01:11:31,955 --> 01:11:36,959
I remember they used to shoot day for night
a lot, which they don't do any more.

972
01:11:40,838 --> 01:11:43,090
It can't go on like this much longer.

973
01:11:44,467 --> 01:11:48,971
Film was so much slower,
and the lenses were so much slower then.

974
01:11:49,055 --> 01:11:50,222
I know.

975
01:11:58,564 --> 01:12:01,566
- Smoking does add something, doesn't it?
- Yes.

976
01:12:01,776 --> 01:12:04,236
...but he'd never let me
transfer out of his outfit.

977
01:12:06,656 --> 01:12:08,198
There is a way.

978
01:12:09,867 --> 01:12:13,412
I've been thinking about it.
You've got to become an officer.

979
01:12:13,579 --> 01:12:17,666
You can take the new extension course,
the one they passed last May.

980
01:12:17,750 --> 01:12:19,835
When you get your commission,
they'd ship you back to the States.

981
01:12:19,919 --> 01:12:21,837
An officer?

982
01:12:21,921 --> 01:12:25,841
Yes. Then I could divorce Dana
and marry you.

983
01:12:25,925 --> 01:12:28,552
I hate officers!
I've always hated officers!

984
01:12:30,596 --> 01:12:34,516
- How old were they?
- In their 30s.

985
01:12:36,519 --> 01:12:37,602
Mid-30s?

986
01:12:37,687 --> 01:12:41,314
I'd say that.
And Clift would have been about the same.

987
01:12:41,774 --> 01:12:45,152
Okay, suppose I did it.
And don't think it's a cinch.

988
01:12:47,113 --> 01:12:52,701
My father had been working
for already about 20 years,

989
01:12:54,454 --> 01:12:59,041
so I'd say this was the pinnacle of his career
to this point.

990
01:13:00,376 --> 01:13:06,631
And it definitely put him in the front ranks
after its release.

991
01:13:06,716 --> 01:13:09,468
So this was a major film for his career.

992
01:13:12,972 --> 01:13:16,558
I've never been so miserable in my life
as I have since I met you.

993
01:13:17,143 --> 01:13:19,061
Neither have I.

994
01:13:19,145 --> 01:13:21,480
I wouldn't trade a minute of it.

995
01:13:21,647 --> 01:13:23,023
Neither would I.

996
01:13:25,276 --> 01:13:28,987
I'll probably make the lousiest officer
in this man's army you ever saw.

997
01:13:30,031 --> 01:13:32,157
You'll make a fine officer.

998
01:13:32,992 --> 01:13:35,327
A remarkable officer.

999
01:13:40,958 --> 01:13:42,501
Thank you.

1000
01:13:45,379 --> 01:13:47,255
Come here.

1001
01:13:49,675 --> 01:13:52,010
Can't you wait until we finish dinner?

1002
01:13:55,473 --> 01:13:57,599
- Honey?
- What?

1003
01:13:57,683 --> 01:13:59,476
I want to marry you.

1004
01:14:01,771 --> 01:14:03,522
You're a funny one.

1005
01:14:03,606 --> 01:14:06,441
Why? Why is it funny
if a guy wants to marry you?

1006
01:14:07,860 --> 01:14:11,113
Because I'm a girl you met
at the New Congress Club.

1007
01:14:11,197 --> 01:14:13,615
That's about two steps up
from the pavement.

1008
01:14:13,699 --> 01:14:17,786
Well, what am I?
I'm a private no-class dogface.

1009
01:14:17,870 --> 01:14:21,206
The way most civilians look at that,
that's two steps up from nothing.

1010
01:14:23,251 --> 01:14:25,669
Prew, I thought we were happy.

1011
01:14:25,753 --> 01:14:27,671
Why do you want to spoil things?

1012
01:14:27,755 --> 01:14:30,882
Look,
I've got a year to go before I reenlist.

1013
01:14:31,384 --> 01:14:35,929
If I can swing sergeant's stripes by then,
they'll let me go back to the States.

1014
01:14:36,013 --> 01:14:38,974
Then you and I can
go back there together, if you'll wait.

1015
01:14:39,058 --> 01:14:42,394
How do you expect to become a sergeant
under that Captain Holmes of yours?

1016
01:14:42,478 --> 01:14:44,396
It's all you can do
to keep out of the stockade.

1017
01:14:48,067 --> 01:14:49,568
I'll fight.

1018
01:14:49,735 --> 01:14:52,320
- No, you're not gonna fight.
- It'd be worth it.

1019
01:14:57,743 --> 01:15:01,121
Prew, it's true we love each other now,

1020
01:15:01,747 --> 01:15:03,456
we need each other,

1021
01:15:04,750 --> 01:15:07,294
but back in the States,
it might be different.

1022
01:15:08,379 --> 01:15:10,297
That ain't the real reason.

1023
01:15:13,509 --> 01:15:16,094
- All right, it's not.
- What is the real reason?

1024
01:15:19,432 --> 01:15:23,268
I won't marry you, because I don't want
to be the wife of a soldier.

1025
01:15:28,774 --> 01:15:31,943
Well, that would be about
the best I could ever do for you.

1026
01:15:35,531 --> 01:15:39,659
Because nobody's gonna
stop me from my plan. Nobody. Nothing.

1027
01:15:39,744 --> 01:15:41,703
Because I want to be proper.

1028
01:15:41,787 --> 01:15:44,581
- Proper?
- Yes, proper.

1029
01:15:45,833 --> 01:15:48,418
In another year, I'll have
enough money saved,

1030
01:15:48,502 --> 01:15:50,629
and then I'm gonna go back
to my hometown in Oregon,

1031
01:15:50,796 --> 01:15:53,548
and I'm gonna build a house
for my mother and myself,

1032
01:15:53,633 --> 01:15:56,343
and join the country club and take up golf.

1033
01:15:57,136 --> 01:16:00,597
And I'll meet the proper man
with the proper position,

1034
01:16:01,557 --> 01:16:06,144
and make a proper wife who can run
a proper home and raise proper children.

1035
01:16:06,938 --> 01:16:10,732
And I'll be happy
because when you're proper, you're safe.

1036
01:16:12,818 --> 01:16:14,945
You got guts, honey.

1037
01:16:15,905 --> 01:16:17,989
I hope you can pull it off.

1038
01:16:26,165 --> 01:16:28,667
I do mean it when I say I need you,

1039
01:16:29,210 --> 01:16:30,919
'cause I'm lonely.

1040
01:16:32,171 --> 01:16:34,047
You think I'm lying, don't you?

1041
01:16:35,800 --> 01:16:38,677
Nobody ever lies about being lonely.

1042
01:16:47,353 --> 01:16:49,688
And don't talk to me about a divorce.

1043
01:16:49,772 --> 01:16:54,192
Why? Because the scandal would spoil
your chances for a promotion?

1044
01:16:54,277 --> 01:16:55,694
I ask you once more.

1045
01:16:55,778 --> 01:16:57,570
I want to know who he is
and where you met him.

1046
01:16:57,655 --> 01:16:59,197
I'm not going to tell you.

1047
01:17:00,700 --> 01:17:05,996
One thing I know. I know he's a civilian.
You'd be too discreet to pick an army man.

1048
01:17:06,080 --> 01:17:09,374
I wonder which is hurt more,
your pride or your curiosity?

1049
01:17:09,458 --> 01:17:11,543
You can't expect to know how
I feel about a thing like this.

1050
01:17:11,627 --> 01:17:14,379
I wonder why men feel
so differently about it than women.

1051
01:17:15,089 --> 01:17:17,007
It's just not the same.

1052
01:17:21,846 --> 01:17:24,889
It's a lovely day.
I think I'll go for a walk.

1053
01:17:27,143 --> 01:17:28,476
Here I am.

1054
01:17:30,813 --> 01:17:32,314
There you are.

1055
01:17:32,648 --> 01:17:33,773
You look just the same.

1056
01:17:33,858 --> 01:17:36,026
- Hardly.
- I know.

1057
01:17:36,444 --> 01:17:38,611
I kept my mouth shut,
and I didn't get in no trouble.

1058
01:17:38,696 --> 01:17:40,155
Did you see Maggio?

1059
01:17:40,239 --> 01:17:44,242
I wasn't even considered to be an actor
in my own mind.

1060
01:17:44,327 --> 01:17:45,577
Yeah.

1061
01:17:45,661 --> 01:17:48,580
You're holding your own against Clift there.

1062
01:17:48,998 --> 01:17:50,915
He's got it down to a system.

1063
01:17:51,208 --> 01:17:52,584
He kicks him a lot, too.

1064
01:17:53,586 --> 01:17:55,920
You know how Maggio's taking it?

1065
01:17:56,339 --> 01:17:59,883
He just keeps spittin' in Fatso's eye.

1066
01:17:59,967 --> 01:18:01,926
Ain't he a hot one?

1067
01:18:03,262 --> 01:18:04,846
He's a good man.

1068
01:18:06,515 --> 01:18:08,933
Was he helpful as an actor to you?

1069
01:18:11,187 --> 01:18:15,357
He was the connection.

1070
01:18:15,775 --> 01:18:19,944
The character was so clear.
He looked right at you.

1071
01:18:20,071 --> 01:18:23,281
- So he made you not have to act.
- I'd never acted with anybody like that.

1072
01:18:23,449 --> 01:18:27,452
So you didn't really have to act,
you just had to respond to him.

1073
01:18:29,038 --> 01:18:31,081
When I saw that close-up,

1074
01:18:31,165 --> 01:18:34,626
I was sitting with some other guy
from the advertising department.

1075
01:18:34,710 --> 01:18:36,711
He said, "What? Hey!"

1076
01:18:38,881 --> 01:18:40,465
Well, this is quite a scene.

1077
01:18:40,549 --> 01:18:44,386
Well, it's an important scene
because it progresses the story.

1078
01:18:44,720 --> 01:18:47,305
You've still got time
to help us win the championship.

1079
01:18:51,894 --> 01:18:55,730
I might have said this before,
but my father said about Clift,

1080
01:18:55,815 --> 01:18:57,565
that because of his intensity

1081
01:18:57,650 --> 01:19:03,154
that he sort of raised the stakes
in terms of the other actors.

1082
01:19:03,239 --> 01:19:05,407
They all had to rise...

1083
01:19:05,491 --> 01:19:10,578
That should have been my reply to you
because that's absolutely the way it was.

1084
01:19:10,663 --> 01:19:13,915
He committed you to what you had to do.

1085
01:19:13,999 --> 01:19:16,084
- So you had to be as excellent as you could.
- You just did.

1086
01:19:16,168 --> 01:19:17,502
Absolutely.

1087
01:19:17,586 --> 01:19:19,045
That's great.

1088
01:19:19,922 --> 01:19:23,508
And it looks like
he wasn't a selfish actor to work with.

1089
01:19:49,660 --> 01:19:51,828
I'll be glad to put
my recommendation on that, Warden.

1090
01:19:51,912 --> 01:19:53,997
You've got service, experience, grade.

1091
01:19:54,081 --> 01:19:56,624
- You'll make an excellent officer.
- Thank you, sir.

1092
01:19:56,709 --> 01:20:00,378
It'd be a feather in my cap, too.
A man from my company.

1093
01:20:02,131 --> 01:20:04,048
At ease. What's the trouble, Sergeant?

1094
01:20:05,384 --> 01:20:08,386
I remember before,
when I got this phone call...

1095
01:20:08,471 --> 01:20:13,475
And that night, I called a friend of mine,
who was a bit of a close friend at the time,

1096
01:20:13,559 --> 01:20:15,643
Lee Marvin, the actor.

1097
01:20:15,728 --> 01:20:17,687
And I said,
"What do you think I should do?"

1098
01:20:17,771 --> 01:20:24,402
He said, "Well, if you do it, and there's
a lot of people around, get in the middle."

1099
01:20:29,700 --> 01:20:31,242
Why don't Prew go for his head?

1100
01:20:31,827 --> 01:20:34,829
- That's you?
- That's me and Don Dubbins.

1101
01:20:41,253 --> 01:20:43,671
I think I got in the middle.

1102
01:20:43,756 --> 01:20:46,799
That was Tim Ryan,
I think, that fellow's name.

1103
01:20:50,763 --> 01:20:52,764
Superman. There's Claude Akins.

1104
01:21:03,275 --> 01:21:06,778
- Come on, Galovitch, fight fair!
- I'll fight any way I want!

1105
01:21:08,113 --> 01:21:10,448
Come on, Prew! Get him!

1106
01:21:12,701 --> 01:21:15,370
How do you think it would have been if

1107
01:21:15,454 --> 01:21:20,708
the captain had been promoted to major
as the script was written,

1108
01:21:20,793 --> 01:21:23,127
instead of the way the Army wanted it?

1109
01:21:23,212 --> 01:21:25,922
It's so satisfying to see him put down.

1110
01:21:43,232 --> 01:21:45,733
Why doesn't that officer stop that fight?

1111
01:21:45,818 --> 01:21:48,319
- What's his name, Major?
- Captain Holmes, sir.

1112
01:22:01,834 --> 01:22:03,251
There I am screaming.

1113
01:22:15,347 --> 01:22:17,473
Ten-hut!

1114
01:22:17,558 --> 01:22:19,642
At ease. What started this?

1115
01:22:19,727 --> 01:22:23,771
Prewitt refused order I gave him,
talked back and started a fight.

1116
01:22:23,856 --> 01:22:25,773
I taught him a lesson.

1117
01:22:26,191 --> 01:22:28,234
You won't disobey
any more orders in my company, Prewitt.

1118
01:22:28,360 --> 01:22:33,281
Sir, I'm sorry, sir, but Private Prewitt's not
to blame, Sergeant Galovitch started it.

1119
01:22:33,407 --> 01:22:34,741
- Thornhill.
- Yes, sir.

1120
01:22:34,867 --> 01:22:36,826
You're in charge of this detail.
What about it?

1121
01:22:36,910 --> 01:22:38,828
He's right, sir. Prewitt done nothing.

1122
01:22:38,912 --> 01:22:41,205
Yes, sir. Galovitch started it.

1123
01:22:42,124 --> 01:22:45,668
That's all. Let's forget it.
Let's get back to our jobs.

1124
01:22:46,879 --> 01:22:49,797
All right, back to work.
Let's go. Break it up.

1125
01:22:53,218 --> 01:22:56,471
If you guys think this means
I'm stepping into a ring, you're wrong.

1126
01:22:56,555 --> 01:22:57,805
You'd better put some iodine on them cuts.

1127
01:22:57,890 --> 01:22:59,140
He's a nice guy.

1128
01:22:59,224 --> 01:23:02,101
- Who's that?
- Claude Akins.

1129
01:23:02,186 --> 01:23:04,103
I remember
he had a television series later on.

1130
01:23:04,188 --> 01:23:05,980
He played a trucker.

1131
01:23:08,525 --> 01:23:10,652
This is where they're playing
the Reenlistment Blues.

1132
01:23:10,736 --> 01:23:11,903
Right.

1133
01:23:12,529 --> 01:23:15,531
Took my dough to town Tuesday

1134
01:23:15,616 --> 01:23:18,785
Found me a big feather bed

1135
01:23:18,869 --> 01:23:23,122
Oh, a big feather bed
A big double bed

1136
01:23:23,207 --> 01:23:26,542
I'll find a job tomorrow

1137
01:23:26,627 --> 01:23:29,379
Tonight I'll sleep like I'm dead

1138
01:23:29,463 --> 01:23:34,092
I'm gonna sleep like I'm dead

1139
01:23:34,176 --> 01:23:37,470
And get up when I choose

1140
01:23:37,554 --> 01:23:40,723
Reenlistment blues

1141
01:23:42,685 --> 01:23:44,227
Hey, Friday.

1142
01:23:44,687 --> 01:23:47,105
- Why are you called Friday?
- I don't know.

1143
01:23:47,356 --> 01:23:49,774
But I was born on a Wednesday.

1144
01:23:50,651 --> 01:23:53,277
I hit the bars Wednesday

1145
01:23:53,737 --> 01:23:57,907
Made me some friends on my own

1146
01:23:57,991 --> 01:24:01,494
Lotta friends on my own

1147
01:24:01,578 --> 01:24:04,831
Found a pretty baby

1148
01:24:04,915 --> 01:24:07,959
She couldn't leave me alone

1149
01:24:08,043 --> 01:24:10,503
Oh, leave me alone

1150
01:24:11,130 --> 01:24:12,922
Interesting actor, really.

1151
01:24:13,757 --> 01:24:15,883
- Yeah.
- Done some great stuff.

1152
01:24:15,968 --> 01:24:18,136
Reenlistment blues

1153
01:24:18,595 --> 01:24:21,889
Reenlistment blues

1154
01:24:22,975 --> 01:24:25,727
I had the misery Thursday

1155
01:24:25,811 --> 01:24:29,230
The walls was movin' I swear

1156
01:24:30,941 --> 01:24:35,486
He was known as being hard to work with
for certain directors.

1157
01:24:35,571 --> 01:24:36,696
He was?

1158
01:24:36,780 --> 01:24:40,408
Well, just because he had a presence,

1159
01:24:40,492 --> 01:24:43,661
and he was intelligent,
and he knew what he wanted to do.

1160
01:24:43,746 --> 01:24:46,706
He knew what looked great on the screen.

1161
01:24:46,790 --> 01:24:50,835
But somehow, my father managed to
get the upper hand there.

1162
01:24:59,011 --> 01:25:01,345
Hey, Prewitt, where you going?

1163
01:25:01,513 --> 01:25:03,765
What do you mean, where am I going?
I'm going to Choy's.

1164
01:25:03,891 --> 01:25:05,892
I'm gonna get me another beer.

1165
01:25:09,855 --> 01:25:12,690
My hitch was up Monday

1166
01:25:12,775 --> 01:25:15,610
Not a dog soldier no more

1167
01:25:15,694 --> 01:25:19,155
I ain't a soldier no more

1168
01:25:20,240 --> 01:25:21,532
Halt!

1169
01:25:23,285 --> 01:25:26,621
- Who goes there?
- A friend.

1170
01:25:26,872 --> 01:25:29,207
Advance, friend, and be recognised!

1171
01:25:39,218 --> 01:25:41,260
Ten-hut!

1172
01:25:41,345 --> 01:25:44,180
Right face! Rear face!

1173
01:25:44,306 --> 01:25:47,225
On your knees! Scrub the floor!

1174
01:25:48,685 --> 01:25:51,979
- Who was the set designer on this?
- Cary Odell.

1175
01:25:52,064 --> 01:25:55,900
Hello, kid.
What are you doing out here all by yourself?

1176
01:25:58,237 --> 01:26:02,490
- I'm gonna get a little drink.
- Sit down. I got a bottle.

1177
01:26:09,081 --> 01:26:10,540
Thanks, Top.

1178
01:26:12,251 --> 01:26:17,004
I gotta hand it to you, kid, the way you
beat up old Galovitch this afternoon.

1179
01:26:17,089 --> 01:26:20,049
Too bad they gotta get you sooner or later.

1180
01:26:28,016 --> 01:26:30,852
Life's crummy, you know it?

1181
01:26:30,936 --> 01:26:34,438
Yes, sir, it's miserable.
Perfectly miserable.

1182
01:26:35,774 --> 01:26:37,191
What do you suppose would happen,

1183
01:26:37,276 --> 01:26:40,194
if a truck was to come along
and run us over?

1184
01:26:41,488 --> 01:26:45,032
- We'd be dead.
- You'd better not sit here any more.

1185
01:26:45,117 --> 01:26:47,618
You'd better get up
and sit over on the side of the road.

1186
01:26:47,703 --> 01:26:50,371
What? What do you mean, I better?

1187
01:26:50,455 --> 01:26:54,876
You've got more to live for than I do.
You got your whole company to take care of.

1188
01:26:54,960 --> 01:26:56,961
You move over, move over
to the other side of the road.

1189
01:26:57,045 --> 01:27:00,006
- Go on.
- I'm older! It don't matter if I die.

1190
01:27:00,090 --> 01:27:02,258
But you got your whole life ahead of you.
Now, don't argue.

1191
01:27:02,342 --> 01:27:04,552
- Go on, get up.
- No, sir, not Prewitt.

1192
01:27:04,636 --> 01:27:07,763
Prewitt stays right here to the bitter end.

1193
01:27:10,183 --> 01:27:13,519
Okay, we'll stay together.

1194
01:27:16,690 --> 01:27:19,984
I don't... I couldn't have got up anyway.

1195
01:27:23,822 --> 01:27:27,325
I got the biggest troubles
in the whole world.

1196
01:27:28,493 --> 01:27:32,622
In terms of the cooperation from the Army,

1197
01:27:32,706 --> 01:27:38,419
I think that was achieved mainly by
Buddy Adler's contacts,

1198
01:27:38,503 --> 01:27:40,838
and getting to the right people,

1199
01:27:43,300 --> 01:27:47,136
and getting the support
that he needed in Hawaii.

1200
01:27:47,846 --> 01:27:52,266
So he was really the one
that was principally responsible for that.

1201
01:27:52,351 --> 01:27:58,189
I remember reading a lot of different notes
on different drafts of the script

1202
01:27:58,857 --> 01:28:01,484
from Joseph Breen in the Breen Office,

1203
01:28:01,568 --> 01:28:07,573
and had very specific
and ludicrous comments

1204
01:28:08,825 --> 01:28:11,452
about who could touch who at what point,

1205
01:28:11,536 --> 01:28:13,871
and when is it okay to show that

1206
01:28:15,332 --> 01:28:19,835
Deborah Kerr and Burt Lancaster
are having an adulterous affair.

1207
01:28:22,506 --> 01:28:25,508
And they were really very intrusive.

1208
01:28:27,177 --> 01:28:31,931
And most of those things,
my father managed to ignore,

1209
01:28:32,015 --> 01:28:36,519
or pretended that he was listening
and was going to do these notes,

1210
01:28:36,603 --> 01:28:38,646
and then wound up not doing them.

1211
01:28:38,730 --> 01:28:43,567
There's a couple of things that
the Breen Office insisted upon.

1212
01:28:44,736 --> 01:28:47,905
There was a big flap
about the scene on the beach,

1213
01:28:49,700 --> 01:28:56,205
in terms of censorship and of what
should be cut and what shouldn't be cut.

1214
01:28:58,083 --> 01:29:02,586
And even the stills
that were used in magazines,

1215
01:29:02,671 --> 01:29:05,423
there was a big flap about that as well.

1216
01:29:07,926 --> 01:29:09,593
But for the time,

1217
01:29:12,556 --> 01:29:18,227
to say anything derogatory or bad
about an institution like the Army

1218
01:29:19,438 --> 01:29:22,982
was really unheard of in that day.

1219
01:29:23,066 --> 01:29:24,400
And also,

1220
01:29:26,278 --> 01:29:28,904
to explore an adulterous relationship

1221
01:29:30,240 --> 01:29:34,952
in a movie about the Army
was also a big no-no.

1222
01:29:37,914 --> 01:29:41,500
They rode me right out,
just like I figured.

1223
01:29:42,461 --> 01:29:45,337
Only the tailgate opened up, Prew,
about a mile back...

1224
01:29:46,298 --> 01:29:49,675
This is one of the famous scenes.

1225
01:29:49,760 --> 01:29:53,679
This probably got Sinatra the award,
this scene.

1226
01:29:56,975 --> 01:30:00,061
Prew. Prew, listen.

1227
01:30:01,605 --> 01:30:03,647
Fatso done it, Prew.

1228
01:30:03,732 --> 01:30:06,150
He likes to whack me in the gut.

1229
01:30:06,234 --> 01:30:10,946
He asks me if it hurts,
and I spit at him like always.

1230
01:30:11,031 --> 01:30:14,658
Only yesterday, it was bad.

1231
01:30:14,743 --> 01:30:18,579
He hit me, he hit me, he hit me.

1232
01:30:19,539 --> 01:30:23,501
I had to get out, Prew. I had to get out.

1233
01:30:24,461 --> 01:30:25,920
Buddy, buddy.

1234
01:30:26,004 --> 01:30:27,838
They gonna send you to the stockade, Prew?

1235
01:30:27,923 --> 01:30:29,590
No, they ain't gonna send me
to the stockade.

1236
01:30:29,674 --> 01:30:31,383
Watch out for Fatso.

1237
01:30:31,468 --> 01:30:33,385
Watch out for Fatso.

1238
01:30:33,470 --> 01:30:35,471
He'll try to crack you.

1239
01:30:35,555 --> 01:30:38,933
And if they put you in the hole,
don't yell.

1240
01:30:39,017 --> 01:30:42,269
We passed the scene, the Diamond Head
scene, but there's this...

1241
01:30:42,354 --> 01:30:45,773
I'm looking at this book
your father put together, his autobiography,

1242
01:30:45,857 --> 01:30:47,399
in which he talks about it.

1243
01:30:47,484 --> 01:30:52,029
But I should have caught that earlier,
but it's very interesting.

1244
01:30:52,114 --> 01:30:53,614
Well, you want to talk about it?

1245
01:30:53,698 --> 01:30:55,407
- Want me to read it?
- Sure.

1246
01:30:55,492 --> 01:30:58,035
He says... This is Fred Zinnemann talking.

1247
01:30:58,120 --> 01:31:04,959
"That scene, regarded as sensational and
extremely provocative a mere 25 years ago,

1248
01:31:05,043 --> 01:31:08,254
"seems harmless and friendly
by today's standards.

1249
01:31:08,338 --> 01:31:10,464
"Although it was shot very much as written,

1250
01:31:10,549 --> 01:31:13,092
"the movie censors,
who knew the script by heart,

1251
01:31:13,176 --> 01:31:18,430
"nevertheless insisted
on deleting four seconds of it.

1252
01:31:19,558 --> 01:31:24,311
"In later years, I found that even more had
been snipped out by theatre projectionists,

1253
01:31:24,396 --> 01:31:26,063
"as a souvenir, no doubt.

1254
01:31:26,148 --> 01:31:27,148
"For many years,

1255
01:31:27,232 --> 01:31:31,819
"the tourist buses used to stop routinely
at this point on the Hawaiian shoreline

1256
01:31:31,903 --> 01:31:37,616
"to let people admire 'the spot where
Burt and Deborah made love in the waves.'

1257
01:31:37,701 --> 01:31:42,204
"It is a curious contribution
we have made to popular culture."

1258
01:31:55,051 --> 01:31:59,013
Monty Clift studied with...
It was very important to him to get the...

1259
01:31:59,097 --> 01:32:04,351
Obviously, he didn't play the bugle himself,
but to get the mouth movements right,

1260
01:32:04,436 --> 01:32:09,273
and he spent a good six months with,
at that time, the best bugler in the world,

1261
01:32:10,442 --> 01:32:15,070
learning how to bugle, or at least
to get the mouth movements down.

1262
01:32:16,615 --> 01:32:22,369
And that bugle was never out of his hand
anywhere, as I say, after the movie was over.

1263
01:32:22,454 --> 01:32:27,374
And he couldn't
get himself out of the Prewitt part.

1264
01:32:27,459 --> 01:32:29,752
He went slightly nuts with it, too.

1265
01:32:31,588 --> 01:32:36,300
The other thing, just in terms of
the detail that they were looking for,

1266
01:32:37,427 --> 01:32:41,347
there was a reference to Prew's character

1267
01:32:41,431 --> 01:32:45,184
being from Harlan County in Kentucky.

1268
01:32:46,311 --> 01:32:49,688
My father and Clift went to great lengths

1269
01:32:49,773 --> 01:32:53,943
to get people in Harlan County,
to record the locals,

1270
01:32:54,027 --> 01:32:58,697
so he could try to mimic their accent,

1271
01:33:00,450 --> 01:33:05,287
which I don't think
anybody picks up these days,

1272
01:33:05,372 --> 01:33:09,833
but anyway, they spent a lot of time
trying to get his accent just right.

1273
01:34:03,930 --> 01:34:05,848
Sergeant Judson?

1274
01:34:06,349 --> 01:34:07,891
You want me?

1275
01:34:08,476 --> 01:34:10,060
Yeah, Fatso.

1276
01:34:10,645 --> 01:34:12,646
I don't like that nickname.

1277
01:34:12,731 --> 01:34:15,399
You want to see me about something?

1278
01:34:15,483 --> 01:34:18,360
Let's step around the corner
where we can talk.

1279
01:34:19,446 --> 01:34:21,071
Okay.

1280
01:34:31,624 --> 01:34:36,003
- Are you sore about something?
- I don't like the way you play the piano.

1281
01:34:39,090 --> 01:34:41,592
- Remember Maggio?
- Oh, the wop?

1282
01:34:41,676 --> 01:34:43,677
Yeah, a real tough monkey.

1283
01:34:43,762 --> 01:34:46,138
- You killed him.
- Did I?

1284
01:34:46,222 --> 01:34:48,140
Well, if I did, he asked for it.

1285
01:34:48,224 --> 01:34:51,310
The army's gonna get you
sooner or later, Fatso.

1286
01:34:52,145 --> 01:34:55,147
But before they do,
I want a piece of you myself.

1287
01:34:56,608 --> 01:34:59,193
I figured that.

1288
01:34:59,277 --> 01:35:01,195
See this knife?

1289
01:35:01,279 --> 01:35:03,739
It's the one you pulled on Maggio.

1290
01:35:19,714 --> 01:35:22,216
When I was just watching this, I'm thinking

1291
01:35:22,300 --> 01:35:28,889
what a great moment,
in terms of positioning and the script.

1292
01:35:30,975 --> 01:35:34,478
The timing and the structure is perfect.

1293
01:35:35,480 --> 01:35:38,148
We're ready for this right now.

1294
01:35:38,233 --> 01:35:42,903
And also, there's a lot more violence
in what you don't see

1295
01:35:42,987 --> 01:35:46,740
- than what you graphically do see.
- Absolutely. You're right.

1296
01:35:46,825 --> 01:35:51,995
All you see are feet disappearing
behind a box, and what you imagine...

1297
01:35:52,080 --> 01:35:54,665
- Watching life go on behind it.
- Yeah.

1298
01:36:37,208 --> 01:36:38,667
Prew!

1299
01:36:39,752 --> 01:36:41,462
What's...

1300
01:36:42,881 --> 01:36:44,715
- Good fall.
- Very good.

1301
01:36:44,841 --> 01:36:46,216
Prew!

1302
01:36:47,552 --> 01:36:49,428
It's all right.

1303
01:36:51,890 --> 01:36:55,434
Don't worry, don't worry.
I ain't gonna die.

1304
01:36:56,311 --> 01:36:58,896
Here we go. The war's about to start.

1305
01:37:11,159 --> 01:37:16,914
Do you remember how long it took
to shoot this scene that you were in?

1306
01:37:16,998 --> 01:37:21,001
- This?
- Well, I mean, the part that you're in.

1307
01:37:21,336 --> 01:37:22,920
- Not very long.
- Really?

1308
01:37:23,004 --> 01:37:25,172
Just as long as it took
for me to run across the field.

1309
01:37:26,674 --> 01:37:31,178
- Did you have to do a lot of takes?
- Three. I think we did it three times.

1310
01:37:32,013 --> 01:37:37,017
I think we rehearsed it
so that I didn't fall on the explosives.

1311
01:37:37,101 --> 01:37:39,603
But wasn't it...
You could have gotten hurt.

1312
01:37:39,687 --> 01:37:43,690
Yeah, they said,
"Drop right here. Don't get any closer."

1313
01:37:44,359 --> 01:37:48,153
- So it was a pretty risky thing for you to do.
- Yeah, it was.

1314
01:37:49,697 --> 01:37:53,534
Were you aware of the risks
before you were doing it?

1315
01:37:55,286 --> 01:37:58,622
I was too excited about
playing a game like a kid,

1316
01:37:58,706 --> 01:38:04,211
you know, running from an aeroplane,
being shot down on a big empty lot.

1317
01:38:05,505 --> 01:38:07,464
"...to the aforesaid Private Prewitt.

1318
01:38:07,882 --> 01:38:11,677
"As mentioned, this included the instigation
of wholly unauthorised tactics..."

1319
01:38:12,470 --> 01:38:15,389
I wonder how
they communicated with the pilot,

1320
01:38:15,473 --> 01:38:17,474
because they didn't have ground-to-air...

1321
01:38:17,559 --> 01:38:22,229
I started running when the plane
was at a certain position over a building,

1322
01:38:22,313 --> 01:38:24,064
and then I started to run.

1323
01:38:24,148 --> 01:38:29,403
And I had done that a few times
so that we got the timing right.

1324
01:38:31,322 --> 01:38:34,074
It seems to be the first thing that you forgot.

1325
01:38:34,158 --> 01:38:36,827
My only regret is that
we have to keep you in uniform

1326
01:38:36,911 --> 01:38:38,912
until a court-martial is concluded.

1327
01:38:40,665 --> 01:38:43,834
This guy was really good,
wasn't he, the captain?

1328
01:38:43,960 --> 01:38:46,837
There is one alternative, General,
if you are so disposed.

1329
01:38:46,921 --> 01:38:52,342
This is the scene
my father couldn't stand having to do,

1330
01:38:53,094 --> 01:38:56,305
because he said it was like
doing a commercial for the Army,

1331
01:38:56,389 --> 01:38:58,015
and it just made him cringe.

1332
01:38:58,099 --> 01:38:59,182
Yeah.

1333
01:38:59,267 --> 01:39:01,893
The quicker you're out of the army,
the better for everybody,

1334
01:39:01,978 --> 01:39:04,021
especially the army.

1335
01:39:05,523 --> 01:39:07,774
That's all, Holmes.

1336
01:39:14,741 --> 01:39:17,200
I know what's been going on in this outfit.

1337
01:39:17,285 --> 01:39:19,661
I know how far some of you
have been out of line.

1338
01:39:19,746 --> 01:39:22,998
If you want to remain noncoms,
you'd better snap into it.

1339
01:39:23,082 --> 01:39:25,459
And another thing, from now on,

1340
01:39:25,543 --> 01:39:28,211
no man's gonna earn his stripes by boxing.

1341
01:39:30,715 --> 01:39:33,133
- Get rid of those.
- Yes, sir.

1342
01:39:33,217 --> 01:39:35,135
Dismissed.

1343
01:39:40,725 --> 01:39:42,976
- About Sergeant Galovitch.
- Yes, sir.

1344
01:39:43,061 --> 01:39:45,812
Bust him.
Sergeant Galovitch is now Private Galovitch.

1345
01:39:45,897 --> 01:39:48,148
Put him in charge of the latrine.

1346
01:39:48,232 --> 01:39:50,150
What are you grinning at?

1347
01:39:50,234 --> 01:39:52,944
I think the company commander
made a wise decision, sir.

1348
01:39:55,907 --> 01:39:57,908
Company "G," Captain Ross.

1349
01:39:59,744 --> 01:40:03,080
- Just a minute. It's for you, Sergeant.
- Thank you, sir.

1350
01:40:06,542 --> 01:40:08,585
Yes, sir?

1351
01:40:10,254 --> 01:40:13,507
Yes, the parcel has already arrived.

1352
01:40:14,801 --> 01:40:16,009
What?

1353
01:40:16,260 --> 01:40:18,929
I've got to see you, Milt. It's important.

1354
01:40:19,597 --> 01:40:23,308
Trying to get back to that aspect of the story.

1355
01:40:23,685 --> 01:40:26,103
Sure, that'd be fine.

1356
01:40:26,187 --> 01:40:29,606
Yeah. I'll be there in about an hour.

1357
01:40:29,691 --> 01:40:30,774
Right.

1358
01:40:30,858 --> 01:40:33,360
- Great script.
- Yeah, I read...

1359
01:40:33,444 --> 01:40:38,615
I was going through the script the other day,
and read the dialogue, and it's timeless.

1360
01:40:39,283 --> 01:40:41,493
It's as effective today as it was then.

1361
01:40:41,577 --> 01:40:44,162
When do you think
you'll get your commission?

1362
01:40:47,625 --> 01:40:49,418
I didn't put it in.

1363
01:40:49,585 --> 01:40:51,670
I filled it out, but I didn't sign it.

1364
01:40:51,838 --> 01:40:55,674
I took it out of my desk a dozen times,
but I couldn't sign it.

1365
01:40:56,342 --> 01:40:57,718
Why?

1366
01:40:59,011 --> 01:41:00,971
But it was the plan.

1367
01:41:01,055 --> 01:41:03,390
- I know, I know.
- It's been weeks.

1368
01:41:03,474 --> 01:41:05,684
You can't just say you'll do a thing
and then not do it.

1369
01:41:05,768 --> 01:41:07,060
Karen, listen to me.

1370
01:41:07,145 --> 01:41:09,980
But why didn't you do it?
Why didn't you tell me?

1371
01:41:11,441 --> 01:41:13,483
Be back in a minute.

1372
01:41:16,112 --> 01:41:18,822
I'm sorry.
I thought you were somebody else.

1373
01:41:24,579 --> 01:41:28,665
I thought it was a guy from our company,
Prewitt, the kid I was telling you about.

1374
01:41:28,750 --> 01:41:31,543
The one that got mixed up with
one of the girls at the New Congress Club.

1375
01:41:31,627 --> 01:41:34,963
He's A.W.O.L. Probably in lots of trouble.

1376
01:41:35,047 --> 01:41:37,591
Robert E. Lee Prewitt, a crazy, no good...

1377
01:41:37,675 --> 01:41:42,345
Actually, Deborah Kerr did a quite believable
American accent, I thought, didn't you?

1378
01:41:42,430 --> 01:41:43,513
Yeah.

1379
01:41:44,348 --> 01:41:45,307
I like that dress.

1380
01:41:45,391 --> 01:41:51,688
I've always liked that
sort of accentuating her neck.

1381
01:41:53,816 --> 01:41:56,234
I know why.

1382
01:41:56,319 --> 01:41:58,403
You don't have to become
an officer now, Milt,

1383
01:41:58,488 --> 01:42:01,031
now that Dana's out of the army.

1384
01:42:01,115 --> 01:42:03,658
You just don't want to marry me.

1385
01:42:03,743 --> 01:42:06,411
You're already married to the army.

1386
01:42:06,496 --> 01:42:08,497
I love you, Karen.

1387
01:42:08,873 --> 01:42:09,873
They don't move their heads.

1388
01:42:09,957 --> 01:42:11,917
I always had this theory that stars,

1389
01:42:12,001 --> 01:42:17,631
people who are really up front,
they do not move their heads.

1390
01:42:18,299 --> 01:42:22,469
Feature players
move their heads a little more.

1391
01:42:22,553 --> 01:42:25,806
And if you watch anchormen,
they never move their heads.

1392
01:42:25,890 --> 01:42:29,893
And people less than anchormen
will sort of move their heads around.

1393
01:42:29,977 --> 01:42:34,064
There's such authority that you get
when you don't move your head.

1394
01:42:34,148 --> 01:42:38,819
And also, the wrong angle,
showing the wrong side of your face...

1395
01:42:38,903 --> 01:42:40,529
When people talk.

1396
01:42:42,031 --> 01:42:44,616
We'll see each other again somewhere.

1397
01:42:45,576 --> 01:42:47,452
Of course we will.

1398
01:42:47,829 --> 01:42:49,663
Somewhere.

1399
01:43:03,553 --> 01:43:07,889
Here it is.
Got it on an inside page already.

1400
01:43:07,974 --> 01:43:13,061
"Still no clue in the fatal stabbing
of Staff Sergeant James R. Judson."

1401
01:43:13,145 --> 01:43:15,272
Did you hear me?

1402
01:43:18,776 --> 01:43:22,153
- Trying to set a new world's record?
- Yeah.

1403
01:43:22,947 --> 01:43:25,615
Yeah, as a matter of fact, I am.

1404
01:43:26,117 --> 01:43:29,369
To the memory of Robert E. Lee Prewitt,

1405
01:43:29,453 --> 01:43:32,539
holder of the new world's record.

1406
01:43:36,419 --> 01:43:38,128
This is you now, isn't it?

1407
01:43:39,297 --> 01:43:40,297
Ten to eight.

1408
01:43:50,975 --> 01:43:52,851
- Everything all right, Top?
- Great.

1409
01:43:53,936 --> 01:43:56,396
This is a beautiful meal
to put in front of a guy on a Sunday morning.

1410
01:43:57,398 --> 01:43:59,316
Congratulations.

1411
01:44:13,164 --> 01:44:16,666
- Sure look pretty over them mountains.
- Don't they, though?

1412
01:44:26,135 --> 01:44:28,762
Sounds like they're dynamiting
down at Wheeler Field.

1413
01:44:28,846 --> 01:44:33,308
Mighty ambitious, huh?
Sunday morning before 8:00?

1414
01:44:43,611 --> 01:44:44,611
Here I come.

1415
01:44:45,363 --> 01:44:47,489
- There's Alvin.
- Here I come.

1416
01:44:49,283 --> 01:44:51,284
- Now!
- Excellent.

1417
01:44:57,458 --> 01:45:00,168
I could do that today, but by accident.

1418
01:45:11,514 --> 01:45:17,143
This shot, my father always loved,
because he said it's like kicking an anthill.

1419
01:45:22,525 --> 01:45:24,275
Look at him.

1420
01:45:26,404 --> 01:45:30,407
There I am. Just lying there, a dead actor.

1421
01:45:30,908 --> 01:45:33,451
The Japanese are bombing Pearl Harbor.

1422
01:45:33,536 --> 01:45:37,497
Please keep in your homes.
Do not go on the streets. This is a real attack.

1423
01:45:37,581 --> 01:45:40,875
Japanese planes are bombing our naval
and army installations.

1424
01:45:42,503 --> 01:45:44,587
All right, all right, you guys, quiet down.

1425
01:45:44,672 --> 01:45:46,589
Quiet! Quiet down!

1426
01:45:46,674 --> 01:45:49,926
Noncoms, get B.A.R.s
and ammunition from the supply room.

1427
01:45:50,011 --> 01:45:51,886
- Get up on the roof. Henderson.
- Right here, Sarge.

1428
01:45:51,971 --> 01:45:53,805
You're in charge of the loading detail.
Get moving.

1429
01:45:53,889 --> 01:45:55,390
Wilson, Dole, let's go.

1430
01:45:55,474 --> 01:45:57,392
The rest of you men, listen to me.

1431
01:45:57,476 --> 01:45:59,936
I want every man to get his rifle,
go to his bunk and stay there.

1432
01:46:00,021 --> 01:46:01,354
And I mean stay there!

1433
01:46:03,607 --> 01:46:04,983
Shut up!

1434
01:46:05,651 --> 01:46:07,736
You'll get your ears shot off
if you go outside.

1435
01:46:07,820 --> 01:46:09,738
You wanna be heroes,
you'll get plenty of chances.

1436
01:46:09,822 --> 01:46:11,781
There'll probably be Japs
in your lap before night.

1437
01:46:11,866 --> 01:46:14,075
Now get moving. We're wasting time.

1438
01:46:14,160 --> 01:46:16,411
Hey, come on. Hurry up.

1439
01:46:17,455 --> 01:46:19,539
Wait. Into the kitchen
and make a pot of coffee.

1440
01:46:19,623 --> 01:46:22,292
- Wait a minute. A barrel of coffee!
- Right, Sarge!

1441
01:46:42,980 --> 01:46:44,230
I don't care.
I can't issue any live ammunitions

1442
01:46:44,315 --> 01:46:45,565
without a signed order from an officer.

1443
01:46:45,649 --> 01:46:47,484
- But the captain ain't here, you jerk!
- I'm sorry.

1444
01:46:47,610 --> 01:46:49,444
- No order, no ammo.
- What's the matter, Leva?

1445
01:46:49,612 --> 01:46:52,489
I got my orders!
Army regulations say that I can't give out...

1446
01:46:57,995 --> 01:46:59,621
What's the matter, are you blind?
Give me them keys!

1447
01:46:59,705 --> 01:47:00,789
I obey my orders, Top.

1448
01:47:00,873 --> 01:47:02,874
Okay, I'll see you get a medal!
Bust it down, boys!

1449
01:47:02,958 --> 01:47:04,876
I warned ya!

1450
01:47:28,234 --> 01:47:30,151
Don't go out there, Warden!
You'll get killed!

1451
01:47:30,236 --> 01:47:32,946
Put your pants on. You'll catch cold!

1452
01:47:59,431 --> 01:48:02,600
Give him a hand with this ammo.
Put that stuff over there.

1453
01:48:08,941 --> 01:48:11,234
Watch your fire, boys,
and lead those planes!

1454
01:48:32,131 --> 01:48:34,716
Friday's gone crazy!
He's blowing the cavalry charge!

1455
01:48:37,928 --> 01:48:39,387
Here they come, boys!

1456
01:49:08,792 --> 01:49:11,961
These are all tricks my father learned
from the shorts department is

1457
01:49:12,046 --> 01:49:18,134
how to tell a story
without a lot of money in little time.

1458
01:49:18,219 --> 01:49:22,305
If you notice that scene,
he just had an American flag,

1459
01:49:22,389 --> 01:49:27,560
saw the plane disappear behind trees,
and then he had somebody set a fireball.

1460
01:49:28,646 --> 01:49:32,732
And it was all done
very economically in one take.

1461
01:49:32,900 --> 01:49:35,443
This is the real McCoy.

1462
01:49:35,527 --> 01:49:38,905
Look out for falling shrapnel.
Keep under cover.

1463
01:49:38,989 --> 01:49:42,659
Blackout and curfew restrictions
will be rigidly enforced.

1464
01:49:42,743 --> 01:49:45,495
Stay in your homes.
Don't use the telephone.

1465
01:49:46,997 --> 01:49:48,915
Rest assured that immediate relay to you...

1466
01:49:48,999 --> 01:49:52,585
Prew! We've been to Queen's Hospital
giving blood.

1467
01:49:52,670 --> 01:49:53,878
The town's a madhouse.

1468
01:49:53,963 --> 01:49:55,964
There's a big house bombed out
on Kuhio Street.

1469
01:49:56,048 --> 01:49:58,675
And the drugstore down
on McCully and King is smashed flat.

1470
01:49:58,759 --> 01:50:02,095
- Man and his wife were killed.
- Your attention, please.

1471
01:50:02,179 --> 01:50:04,889
Listen to this carefully and keep calm.

1472
01:50:04,974 --> 01:50:08,434
The danger of an invasion continues to exist,

1473
01:50:08,519 --> 01:50:12,230
and the planes have been
identified as Japanese.

1474
01:50:12,940 --> 01:50:14,983
Who do they think they're fighting?

1475
01:50:15,442 --> 01:50:18,987
They're picking trouble
with the best army in the world.

1476
01:50:20,281 --> 01:50:21,531
Where are you going?

1477
01:50:22,574 --> 01:50:25,743
I gotta get back.
I gotta get back to the company.

1478
01:50:25,828 --> 01:50:29,956
- The company? But why?
- Why?

1479
01:50:30,207 --> 01:50:33,042
But you can't. You're not well yet.

1480
01:50:33,585 --> 01:50:36,629
Besides, you're A.W.O.L.
They'll throw you in the stockade.

1481
01:50:36,714 --> 01:50:38,715
They'll be throwing them out of the stockade.

1482
01:50:38,882 --> 01:50:41,718
- They need every guy they can get.
- But your side'll open up.

1483
01:50:41,802 --> 01:50:44,679
They'll find out it was you
who killed that soldier.

1484
01:50:44,763 --> 01:50:48,057
Once I report in to the company,
they'll take care of me.

1485
01:50:48,183 --> 01:50:49,976
I'll be all right once I get back.

1486
01:50:50,060 --> 01:50:53,438
But you'll never make it!
There's patrols all over!

1487
01:50:53,522 --> 01:50:56,607
I'll make it. I know a shortcut.

1488
01:50:58,902 --> 01:51:01,070
Prew, stay till morning.

1489
01:51:01,155 --> 01:51:03,906
Maybe if you stay till morning,
you'll change your mind.

1490
01:51:11,415 --> 01:51:13,333
Oh, Prew, don't go!

1491
01:51:13,417 --> 01:51:15,501
I'll do anything you want.

1492
01:51:15,586 --> 01:51:20,006
We can go back to the States together.
We can even get married.

1493
01:51:23,510 --> 01:51:26,721
If you go now,
I'll never see you again, I know it.

1494
01:51:26,805 --> 01:51:28,598
I'm sorry.

1495
01:51:33,937 --> 01:51:36,356
What do you want to go back
to the army for?

1496
01:51:36,440 --> 01:51:39,192
What did the army ever
do for you besides treat you like dirt

1497
01:51:39,276 --> 01:51:42,862
and give you one awful going-over
and get your friend killed?

1498
01:51:42,946 --> 01:51:45,406
What do you want to go back to the army for?

1499
01:51:45,491 --> 01:51:48,201
What do I want to go back to the army for?
I'm a soldier.

1500
01:51:48,285 --> 01:51:50,286
A soldier? A soldier?

1501
01:51:50,371 --> 01:51:54,082
A regular! From the regular army!
A 30-year man!

1502
01:51:56,126 --> 01:52:00,171
I gotta turn off the lights
'cause of the blackout outside.

1503
01:52:13,811 --> 01:52:16,521
They say they've seen parachutists
land up in the hills.

1504
01:52:16,605 --> 01:52:19,982
I ain't worried about them.
Saboteurs is what worries me.

1505
01:52:20,067 --> 01:52:22,985
Yeah. I bet they're operating
all over these islands.

1506
01:53:36,477 --> 01:53:38,478
Halt!

1507
01:53:40,397 --> 01:53:42,398
Halt!

1508
01:53:52,951 --> 01:53:54,243
Halt!

1509
01:54:07,257 --> 01:54:10,801
My hitch was up Monday

1510
01:54:10,886 --> 01:54:14,555
Not a dog soldier no more

1511
01:54:14,640 --> 01:54:18,601
Soldier no more

1512
01:54:19,937 --> 01:54:23,856
They give me all that money

1513
01:54:23,941 --> 01:54:27,693
So much my pockets is sore

1514
01:54:30,531 --> 01:54:32,698
Do you know this man, Sergeant?

1515
01:54:32,783 --> 01:54:34,700
Yes, sir.

1516
01:54:34,785 --> 01:54:36,911
He didn't have any regular identification.

1517
01:54:36,995 --> 01:54:39,497
They found a card on him with his name.

1518
01:54:39,581 --> 01:54:41,707
Seems to be a membership in a club.

1519
01:54:41,792 --> 01:54:43,876
- The New Congress Club.
- Yes, sir.

1520
01:54:43,961 --> 01:54:46,128
You'd better take care of these, Sergeant.

1521
01:54:50,634 --> 01:54:53,511
- Was this man a friend of yours?
- Yes, sir.

1522
01:54:53,595 --> 01:54:56,347
He must've been trying to reach our
company position up the beach here.

1523
01:54:56,431 --> 01:54:57,890
Then why didn't he halt?

1524
01:54:57,975 --> 01:55:01,060
He was always a hardhead, sir,
but he was a good soldier.

1525
01:55:01,144 --> 01:55:03,938
He loved the army
more than any soldier I ever knew.

1526
01:55:04,064 --> 01:55:07,817
I see. I'm sorry, Sergeant.

1527
01:55:14,908 --> 01:55:19,912
James Jones wrote to Buddy Adler in a letter
about the ending of the movie

1528
01:55:22,416 --> 01:55:25,501
and what he hoped would be conveyed.

1529
01:55:26,253 --> 01:55:31,924
And what he said he wanted to show
was that life goes on, people move on.

1530
01:55:33,260 --> 01:55:36,429
Prew's death is nothing but a small ripple

1531
01:55:36,513 --> 01:55:40,099
in a vast moving tide
that stops to mourn for no man.

1532
01:55:41,935 --> 01:55:45,771
He said,
"If you get that right, you've got the movie."

1533
01:55:46,064 --> 01:55:48,149
We ain't got all night!

1534
01:56:10,172 --> 01:56:12,131
It's very beautiful, isn't it?

1535
01:56:16,386 --> 01:56:20,139
I think it's the most beautiful place
I ever saw in my life.

1536
01:56:21,558 --> 01:56:24,310
I can almost see where I worked from here.

1537
01:56:27,689 --> 01:56:30,191
Well, it's a great way for me to end my...

1538
01:56:31,485 --> 01:56:35,905
Or put some sort of a period
on my connection with this movie,

1539
01:56:35,989 --> 01:56:40,493
starting with washing my car
one Saturday afternoon,

1540
01:56:40,577 --> 01:56:43,663
and being here with Tim,

1541
01:56:43,747 --> 01:56:49,335
and thinking about
my whole history with Fred Zinnemann

1542
01:56:49,419 --> 01:56:53,255
and how he played a big part in my career.

1543
01:56:54,007 --> 01:56:56,842
I'm honoured.

1544
01:56:58,011 --> 01:57:04,016
I have to say,
I'm delighted to be here today with Alvin,

1545
01:57:04,851 --> 01:57:07,687
who not only do I know separately
from my father,

1546
01:57:07,771 --> 01:57:12,191
having worked with him
on a movie called Straight Time,

1547
01:57:12,275 --> 01:57:14,777
but also through my father on Julia,

1548
01:57:15,862 --> 01:57:20,282
and from having heard all the stories
about him on From Here to Eternity.

1549
01:57:21,702 --> 01:57:26,539
I think it was wonderful
to watch this movie again,

1550
01:57:26,623 --> 01:57:29,875
and to see how it holds up today,

1551
01:57:30,627 --> 01:57:34,213
and how truly wonderful it was then
and still is today.

1552
01:57:34,297 --> 01:57:41,220
And I hope everybody that is going
to see it now likes it as much as I do.

1553
01:57:42,000 --> 01:57:45,117


